<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1922-01-07T02:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1922-01-07T02:00:00-05:00" n="22" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d22">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A4a/5: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Siam</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Williams</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg></opener>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Bangkok</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-01-07T14:00:00+07:00"><hi rend="italic">January
                                            7, 1922—2 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received 8:44
                                    p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                            <p>1. In conversation yesterday at Foreign Office, the Minister of
                                Foreign Affairs informally expressed Siamese support of arrangement
                                    <pb facs="0162" n="42" xml:id="pg_42"/> for four-power agreement
                                providing for common counsel in the solution of problems in
                                Pacific.</p>
                            <p>Siam probably would welcome invitation to indicate diplomatic
                                adherence to agreement if the initiative in this connection came
                                from the Government of the United States.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Williams</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>